{
  "title": "Soil-less Culture",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8661db89e09e2437",
      "text": "Soil-less culture is the method of growing\nagricultural crops without the use of soil.\nInstead of soil, various inert growing media,\nalso called substrates, are used. These media\nprovide plant support and moisture retention.\nIrrigation systems are integrated within these\nmedia, thereby introducing a nutrient solution\nto the plants’ root zones - [http://www.fao.org/3/a-i4021e.pdf fao.org]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1083ea13ccc031cc",
      "text": "This solution provides\nall of the necessary nutrients for plant growth.\nThe most common method of soil-less culture\nis hydroponics, which includes growing plants\neither on a substrate or in an aqueous medium\nwith bare roots. There are many designs of\nhydroponic systems, each serving a different\npurpose, but all systems share these basic characteristics."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9ff5cc53dc08baa3",
      "text": "Soil-less agriculture has been used to reduce pests and soil-borne diseases affecting\nmonoculture crops. Hydroponics can in fact control soil-borne pests and diseases\nby avoiding the contact between plants and soil, and because soil-less media can be\nsterilized and reused between crops. This reuse of substrates meets the particular\ndemands of intensive production. Some substrates are far better than soil, particularly\nin terms of water-holding capacity and oxygen supply at the root zone. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c1c736d3db21e9c4",
      "text": "Farmers have\nalso improved plant performance through increased control over several crucial factors\nof plant growth. Nutrient availability at plant roots is better manipulated, monitored\nand real-time controlled, leading to higher quantitative and qualitative productions."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6176f2f808229ff6",
      "text": "Moreover, most soil-less culture methods use a fraction of the water necessary for\ntraditional soil-based production because the nutrient solution is recycled."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c71b9c9f40bacb13",
      "text": "Soil-less agriculture is one aspect of the major scientific, economic and technological\ndevelopments in the general field of agriculture over the last 200 years. In general, but predominately in developed nations in temperate climates, there has been an increasing\ndemand for out-of-season, high-value crops. Partly, this is a result of widespread\nimprovements in living standards. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bb0cf94098dfdd2c",
      "text": "This increase in demand has led to the expansion of\nmany types of protected cultivation systems to boost production capacity and prolong\nthe supply of crops throughout the year. Within these protected systems, crops can\nbe grown in soil. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1d22359a9fd99123",
      "text": "However, in order to stay competitive with open-field agriculture\nproduction, intensity has had to increase in order to offset the higher production costs\nassociated with controlled environment agriculture. As a result, there has been a shift\nfrom soil production to soil-less culture to address the changing needs of agriculture.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4768fbf3cd7a9344",
      "text": "This approach provides alternatives to toxic soil sterilization to control pests and\npathogens, and can help to overcome the soil-tiredness problems that monoculture\npractices have brought."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9b733e5b85859003",
      "text": "Beyond its significantly higher yields compared with traditional agriculture,\nsoil-less agriculture is also important because of its higher water- and fertilizer-use\nefficiency, which makes hydroponics the most suitable farming technique in arid\nregions or wherever nutrient dispersal is an issue for both environmental and economic\nreasons. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3b7a3ce10de9d09c",
      "text": "The offset of soil makes hydroponics an indispensable solution in areas where\narable land is not available. Soil-less agriculture can instead be developed in arid lands,\nin saline-prone areas, as well as in urban and suburban environments or wherever\nthe competition for land and water or unfavourable climatic conditions require the\nadoption of intensive production systems. The high productivity for the small space\nrequired makes soil-less agriculture an interesting method for food security or for the\ndevelopment of micro-scale farming with zero food miles."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "26996ca256a3c99b",
      "text": "To summarize, the four main reasons why soil-less culture is an expanding agricultural\npractice are: decreased presence of soil-borne diseases and pathogens because of sterile\nconditions; improved growing conditions that can be manipulated to meet optimal plant\nrequirements leading to increased yields; increased water- and fertilizer-use efficiency;\nand the possibility to develop agriculture where suitable land is not available. In\naddition with the rising in demand for chemical- and pesticide-free produce and more\nsustainable agricultural practices, there has been extensive research into organic and soilless\nmethods. Section 6.1 discusses these differences in more detail."
    }
